The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, May 29, 2004 				 ITC net profit up 16%
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Calcutta, May 28: ITC has posted a 16.2 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 1,592.85 crore in 2003-04 compared with Rs 1,371.35 crore in the previous year.																								Pre-tax profit has increased 12.8 per cent to Rs 2,319 crore from Rs 2,056.19 crore in 2002-03.																								The companys fourth-quarter net profit has jumped 19.68 per cent to Rs 387.06 crore compared with Rs 323.42 crore in the year-ago period.																								The ITC board has recommended a dividend of 200 per cent compared with 150 per cent in the previous year. This will entail a total cash outflow of Rs 559 crore, comprising the proposed dividend of Rs 495 crore and income tax of Rs 64 crore on the dividend outgo.																								The companys turnover (income from operations) rose 7.2 per cent to Rs 11,815 crore in 2003-04 against Rs 11,024.88 crore in the previous year.																								After adjusting for the once-off opportunity of rice exports in 2002-03, underlying topline growth stood at an impressive 11.8 per cent over last year, the company said.																								Net income during the fourth quarter increased to Rs 1,938.16 crore from Rs 1,579.93 crore in the year-ago period. Profit before tax stood at Rs 524.26 crore against Rs 463.36 crore despite a marginal increase in interest charges at Rs 8.18 crore against Rs 5.96 crore in the corresponding previous period.																								In the cigarette business, the company has recorded a revenue growth of 5.3 per cent during the year, mainly because of a better product mix and a 3 per cent growth in volume sales. The revenues shot up to Rs 9,230.27 crore from Rs 8,764 crore in the previous year.																								The new FMCG businesses of the company contributed Rs 304 crore to its topline.																								Revenue from the companys hotel business also rose to Rs 257.53 crore from Rs 193.41 crore in 2002-03, while agri-business rose to Rs 1,708.77 crore from Rs 1,658.14 crore in 2002-03.
